      <span class="tag">Comparison</span>
      <h1>CalDigit TS4 vs Satechi Thunderbolt 4 Dock: Which Is Better in 2026?</h1>
      <div class="meta">Updated June 2026 · 8 min read</div>
    </div>

    <nav class="toc">
      <h2>Table of Contents</h2>
      <ol>
        <li><a href="#overview">Overview</a></li>
        <li><a href="#specs">Specs Comparison</a></li>
        <li><a href="#pros-cons">Pros and Cons</a></li>
        <li><a href="#performance">Performance</a></li>
        <li><a href="#price">Price</a></li>
        <li><a href="#who-wins">Who Wins</a></li>
        <li><a href="#recommendation">Final Recommendation</a></li>
        <li><a href="#faq">FAQ</a></li>
      </ol>
    </nav>

    <h2 id="overview">Overview</h2>
    <p>The CalDigit TS4 and the Satechi Thunderbolt 4 Dock are two of the most popular Thunderbolt 4 docks for connecting a laptop to a full desktop workstation, and in 2026 they remain the leading choices for Mac and Windows users who need a single cable to drive multiple displays, high-speed peripherals, and power delivery. The CalDigit TS4 is the flagship of the category, boasting 18 ports, 98W of host charging, and a reputation for rock-solid firmware stability. The Satechi Thunderbolt 4 Dock is the design-forward challenger, offering a sleek aluminum body, dual 4K display support, and 96W charging at a lower price.</p>

    <p>Both docks are built on the Intel Thunderbolt 4 controller, which means both deliver 40Gbps of total bandwidth, support for dual 4K displays at 60Hz, and downstream Thunderbolt ports for daisy-chaining. The differences are in port count, power delivery, thermal design, and firmware polish. The TS4 is the more comprehensive docking station, packing every port a power user could want into a single aluminum enclosure with an integrated heat sink. The Satechi dock is the more compact and affordable option, trading a few ports and a small amount of power for a lower price and a footprint that matches Apple's industrial design language.</p>

    <p>For buyers choosing between them, the decision comes down to how many peripherals you need to connect, how much power your laptop requires, and how much you value firmware stability versus price and aesthetics. After testing both docks across months of daily use with Mac and Windows laptops, dual monitors, and high-speed external storage, here is the detailed comparison.</p>

    <h2 id="specs">Specs Comparison</h2>
