    <h2 id="pros-cons">Pros and Cons</h2>
    <h3>CalDigit TS4</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>✓ Industry-leading 18 ports cover nearly every connectivity need</li>
      <li>✓ 98W power delivery charges the most demanding laptops</li>
      <li>✓ 2.5GbE ethernet is faster than the Satechi's 1GbE</li>
      <li>✓ Supports single 8K display in addition to dual 4K</li>
      <li>✓ Most reliable firmware on macOS with frequent updates</li>
      <li>✓ Excellent thermal design stays cool under sustained load</li>
      <li>✗ Premium price of $399 is $100 more than the Satechi</li>
      <li>✗ Larger footprint takes up more desk space</li>
      <li>✗ Requires its own 230W power brick</li>
    </ul>
    <h3>Satechi Thunderbolt 4 Dock</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>✓ Sleek aluminum design matches Apple aesthetics</li>
      <li>✓ $299 price is $100 less than the CalDigit TS4</li>
      <li>✓ Compact footprint fits neatly under a monitor</li>
      <li>✓ Dual 4K @ 60Hz display support for most setups</li>
      <li>✓ 96W power delivery handles most laptops</li>
      <li>✗ Only 9 ports, far fewer than the TS4's 18</li>
      <li>✗ 1GbE ethernet is slower than the TS4's 2.5GbE</li>
      <li>✗ No 8K display support</li>
      <li>✗ Firmware updates less frequent than CalDigit's</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="performance">Performance</h2>
    <p>Port selection and connectivity are where the CalDigit TS4 establishes its lead. With 18 ports — including five downstream Thunderbolt ports, five USB-A ports, three USB-C data ports, two DisplayPort 1.4 outputs, 2.5GbE ethernet, UHS-II SD and microSD readers, and an audio combo jack — the TS4 is effectively a complete desktop I/O hub in a single enclosure. You can connect dual 4K monitors, an external NVMe SSD, a wired keyboard and mouse, an audio interface, a wired ethernet connection, and still have Thunderbolt ports free for daisy-chaining additional devices. The Satechi dock's 9 ports cover the essentials — three Thunderbolt 4 downstream ports, four USB-A ports, one DisplayPort, ethernet, SD readers, and audio — but they run out faster for users with many peripherals.</p>

    <p>Display performance is comparable for most users, with both docks driving dual 4K displays at 60Hz over Thunderbolt 4. The TS4 pulls ahead for ultra-high-resolution setups because it supports a single 8K display at 30Hz, which the Satechi dock does not. For the majority of users running two 4K monitors, both docks perform identically, with crisp, lag-free output and no noticeable latency. Power delivery is nearly tied, with the TS4 offering 98W and the Satechi 96W — both enough to fast-charge any modern MacBook or Windows laptop while under load, including the 16-inch MacBook Pro.</p>

    <p>Where the TS4 separates itself is in firmware stability and thermal performance. CalDigit has a long track record of reliable Thunderbolt docks, and the TS4 benefits from frequent firmware updates and broad compatibility across macOS and Windows. In months of testing, it never dropped a display, disconnected a peripheral, or required a restart. The Satechi dock is reliable for the most part and its aluminum design is genuinely attractive on a desk, but it has a slightly higher incidence of firmware quirks — occasional display flicker after sleep, or a USB device needing a replug after the laptop wakes — that CalDigit resolves more consistently. The TS4's larger aluminum body with an integrated heat sink also stays cooler under sustained heavy load, while the more compact Satechi can get warm to the touch when driving dual displays and multiple USB devices simultaneously. For mission-critical workstations, the TS4's polish justifies its premium.</p>

    <h2 id="price">Price</h2>
    <p>The Satechi Thunderbolt 4 Dock costs $299, making it $100 cheaper than the CalDigit TS4's $399 price. For buyers who need dual 4K displays, 96W laptop charging, and a handful of USB ports, the Satechi delivers the core Thunderbolt 4 dock experience at a genuinely competitive price, and its design is a strong selling point for Apple-focused setups.</p>

    <p>The CalDigit TS4's $399 premium buys meaningful upgrades: 18 ports versus 9, 98W versus 96W power delivery, 2.5GbE versus 1GbE ethernet, 8K display support, and superior firmware stability. For power users who connect many peripherals, run high-resolution displays, or rely on their dock for daily professional work, those upgrades are worth the $100. For users with simpler needs — a laptop, two monitors, a keyboard, a mouse, and maybe an external drive — the Satechi dock covers the essentials for less, and the savings can go toward a better monitor or accessories. Both docks include 2-year warranties, so long-term coverage is comparable. The value calculation comes down to how heavily you will load the dock: light to moderate users will be happy with the Satechi, while heavy users will get their money's worth from the TS4.</p>

    <h2 id="who-wins">Who Wins</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>For maximum connectivity:</strong> CalDigit TS4 wins because its 18 ports, including five downstream Thunderbolt ports and 2.5GbE ethernet, handle the most peripheral-heavy workstations.</li>
      <li><strong>For firmware stability and reliability:</strong> CalDigit TS4 wins because its consistent firmware updates and thermal design deliver a more dependable experience, especially on macOS.</li>
      <li><strong>For value and design:</strong> Satechi Thunderbolt 4 Dock wins because its $299 price and sleek aluminum body deliver dual 4K display support and 96W charging for $100 less than the TS4.</li>
      <li><strong>For ultra-high-resolution displays:</strong> CalDigit TS4 wins because it supports a single 8K display in addition to dual 4K, a capability the Satechi dock lacks.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="recommendation">Final Recommendation</h2>
    <p>If you want the most capable and reliable Thunderbolt 4 dock available, the CalDigit TS4 is the clear choice. Its 18 ports cover virtually every connectivity scenario, its 98W power delivery charges any laptop, its 2.5GbE ethernet future-proofs your wired network, and its firmware stability is the best in the category. At $399 it is an investment, but for a permanent desktop workstation that you connect to every day, the TS4's combination of port count, power, and polish justifies the premium.</p>

    <p>If you need a solid Thunderbolt 4 dock for a simpler setup and want to spend less, the Satechi Thunderbolt 4 Dock is an excellent value. Its dual 4K display support, 96W charging, and clean aluminum design make it ideal for a laptop-plus-dual-monitor workstation, and at $299 it saves you $100 over the TS4 while delivering the core Thunderbolt 4 experience. For users who do not need 18 ports or 8K display support, the Satechi is the smarter buy.</p>

    <p>The deciding question is how heavily you will use the dock: choose the CalDigit TS4 if you connect many peripherals, value rock-solid firmware, or need 8K or 2.5GbE; choose the Satechi Thunderbolt 4 Dock if you want dual 4K displays and reliable charging in a more affordable, design-forward package. Both are excellent Thunderbolt 4 docks that will turn your laptop into a true desktop workstation with a single cable.</p>
    <p>Read our full reviews: <a href="/reviews/caldigit-ts4-review/">CalDigit TS4 Review</a> and <a href="/reviews/satechi-thunderbolt-4-dock-review/">Satechi Thunderbolt 4 Dock Review</a>.</p>
    <p>Learn more about our <a href="/editorial-policy/">editorial policy</a>.</p>

    <h2 id="faq">FAQ</h2>
    <div class="faq">
      <details>
        <summary>Is the CalDigit TS4 better than the Satechi Thunderbolt 4 Dock?</summary>
        <p>The CalDigit TS4 is better for power users who need the maximum port count (18 ports), 98W power delivery, and the most refined firmware and thermal performance. The Satechi Thunderbolt 4 Dock is better for buyers who want a more affordable, compact dock that still drives dual 4K displays at 60Hz and delivers 96W of charging in a sleek aluminum design.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can the CalDigit TS4 and Satechi Thunderbolt 4 Dock drive two 4K displays?</summary>
        <p>Yes, both docks support dual 4K displays at 60Hz over Thunderbolt 4, provided your host computer has a Thunderbolt 4 port and the displays connect via Thunderbolt or DisplayPort. The CalDigit TS4 additionally supports a single 8K display, which the Satechi dock does not.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Which Thunderbolt 4 dock is better for Mac, the CalDigit TS4 or the Satechi?</summary>
        <p>Both are fully compatible with Mac and Windows. The CalDigit TS4 has a longer track record of firmware stability on macOS and is widely regarded as the most reliable Thunderbolt 4 dock for Mac users. The Satechi dock is also Mac-compatible and its aluminum design matches Apple aesthetics, but some users report occasional firmware quirks that CalDigit resolves more quickly.</p>
      </details>
    </div>

